network_overview: Capture at a 5G core UPF-facing point shows PFCP (UDP/8805) control signaling with multiple request timeouts and several PFCP responses carrying cause "Rule creation / modification Failure" (cause=73). In parallel, GTPv2-C signaling includes responses with cause code 128 labeled "S1-U Path Failure", while Diameter (TCP/3868) exchanges include at least one DIAMETER_SUCCESS (result code 2001).

root_causes.issue: PFCP rule creation/modification failures (Cause=73) on PFCP-Msg-51 responses
root_causes.description: Three PFCP-Msg-51 responses explicitly carry cause=73 labeled "Rule creation / modification Failure", indicating that the PFCP peer rejected or failed the requested rule operation for those sessions/SEIDs. This is directly evidenced in frames 9/17/25 with different SEIDs (0x...5d0110, 0x...5e0110, 0x...5f0110).
root_causes.impact: Can prevent correct programming of user-plane forwarding/rules for the affected PFCP sessions, potentially impacting data path establishment/modification for those sessions (exact service impact not directly observable in this capture).
root_causes.confidence_justification: Direct evidence: PFCP responses with explicit failure cause 73 observed multiple times. The exact internal reason for the rule failure is not present in the provided fields (no additional IEs shown), so only the PFCP cause-level failure can be concluded.

root_causes.issue: PFCP request timeouts / missing responses in capture
root_causes.description: At least five PFCP requests are marked status "no_response" and are also flagged by temporal anomalies as PFCP request timed out (no response captured). This indicates PFCP response packets were not observed for those specific requests within the trace window.
root_causes.impact: Degraded PFCP control-plane reliability/visibility for session establishment/modification/association-type procedures represented by PFCP-Msg-54 and PFCP-Msg-50 in this capture; may lead to delayed or failed control-plane procedures depending on retransmission/timeout handling (retransmissions not explicitly listed in evidence).
root_causes.confidence_justification: Strong evidence that responses were not captured (status=no_response plus temporal anomaly entries). However, this capture alone cannot distinguish whether the peer truly did not respond versus responses being missed due to capture point/filters/asymmetric routing.

root_causes.issue: GTPv2-C failures indicated by Cause=128 (S1-U Path Failure)
root_causes.description: Two GTPv2-C responses include cause code 128 labeled "S1-U Path Failure". This is explicit error signaling from the GTPv2-C peer for the associated transactions.
root_causes.impact: Indicates failure related to the user-plane path as signaled by GTPv2-C cause 128; may block or degrade bearer/user-plane establishment/maintenance for the involved TEIDs (exact bearer/procedure not provided in the evidence).
root_causes.confidence_justification: Direct evidence of GTPv2-C failure cause 128 is present. The precise triggering condition and the specific 3GPP procedure (by fully decoded message name and IEs) are not provided, limiting confidence on the broader scenario beyond 'GTPv2-C reported S1-U Path Failure'.

inconclusive_aspects.aspect: Whether PFCP timeouts reflect real peer non-response versus capture visibility gap
inconclusive_aspects.reason: Evidence only shows 'status=no_response' and timeout flags; it does not prove the peer never transmitted a response.
inconclusive_aspects.additional_capture_needed: Simultaneous captures on both PFCP endpoints (10.47.145.117 and 10.130.9.119) or at a SPAN/TAP that guarantees bidirectional visibility for UDP/8805 during the same timestamps.

inconclusive_aspects.aspect: Exact PFCP procedure names and rule identifiers (PDR/FAR/QER/URR) that failed
inconclusive_aspects.reason: Provided evidence includes PFCP message types (PFCP-Msg-50/51/54/55) and Cause only; no PFCP IE-level details are included.
inconclusive_aspects.additional_capture_needed: PFCP decode including IE details for the failing PFCP-Msg-51 responses (e.g., which rule operation failed) and the corresponding request contents.

inconclusive_aspects.aspect: End-to-end user-plane (GTP-U) forwarding impact and data-plane packet loss
inconclusive_aspects.reason: While a 'GTP-U Tunnel' summary exists, no per-packet GTP-U user-plane outcomes or throughput/continuity evidence is included, and GTP-U is not listed among 'Protocols Detected'.
inconclusive_aspects.additional_capture_needed: User-plane capture including GTP-U packet headers/payload at the same observation point and timeframe, plus correlation to the affected PFCP SEIDs/TEIDs.

inconclusive_aspects.reason: No SIP/SDP/RTP observed; IMS/voice analysis section shows no calls and no media metrics.
inconclusive_aspects.additional_capture_needed: Capture at an IMS/SIP signaling point for SIP/SDP and at a media plane point where RTP is visible, if voice service troubleshooting is required.

recommendations.action: Investigate PFCP rule failure cause=73 occurrences by correlating the failing PFCP-Msg-51 responses (frames 9/17/25) with the exact request contents (PFCP-Msg-50 _seq=852494/852495/852496) and rule IEs.
recommendations.rationale: Three explicit PFCP failures with cause 73 indicate rule programming problems; without IE-level details, the failing rule type/operation is not identifiable from this capture.

recommendations.action: Validate PFCP bidirectional connectivity/visibility between 10.47.145.117 and 10.130.9.119 for UDP/8805 around timestamps 1697719684.987–1697719712.798, including packet capture on both ends.
recommendations.rationale: Five PFCP requests are marked no_response and flagged as timed out; dual-ended capture can distinguish true peer non-response from capture loss/asymmetric visibility.

recommendations.action: Correlate GTPv2-C failures (cause=128) with the specific GTPv2-C procedures represented by message types 0x15 and 0x11 and the associated TEIDs (0x82000394, 0x82100328).
recommendations.rationale: Two explicit GTPv2-C responses signal 'S1-U Path Failure'; mapping these to the exact control-plane operation will narrow which bearer/session operation is failing.

session_analysis.signaling_health: PFCP signaling shows mixed outcomes: explicit success causes (cause=1) are present (frames 4 and 31), but multiple PFCP-Msg-51 failures with cause=73 (frames 9/17/25) and multiple PFCP requests with no captured responses (frames 2/8/16/24/30) indicate degraded or partially observed PFCP control-plane behavior. GTPv2-C includes explicit failure causes (cause=128) on two responses (frames 3 and 32). Diameter shows at least one successful transaction (Cmd-272 result=2001) (frame 7).
session_analysis.user_plane_health: Not determinable from the provided evidence at packet level: while GTPv2-C reports cause=128 (S1-U Path Failure), the capture does not provide user-plane (GTP-U) packet evidence/metrics to confirm actual data forwarding status.
session_analysis.voice_quality: Not observable at this capture point (no SIP/SDP/RTP evidence provided).
session_analysis.cross_plane_correlation: There is temporal proximity between PFCP control events and GTPv2-C failure indications (e.g., around 1697719684.987 both PFCP and GTPv2-C messages occur), but the capture lacks explicit common identifiers across planes (no subscriber IDs; limited decoded IEs), so definitive cross-plane causality cannot be proven from this evidence alone.
